'''Tempus fugit''' is a [[Latin (language)|latin]] expression meaning ''time flies''. Today it's frequently used as an inscription on clocks or artwork. The expression was first used in the verse ''Georgica'' written by Roman poet [[Virgil]], the particular line in his verse was: ''Sed fugit interea, fugit irreparabile tempus'', which means roughly: ''Meanwhile the irreplaceable time flies''.

The phrase was further popularized by its usage in [[Stephen King|Stephen King's]] novel [[Hearts in Atlantis]].

It is also composition by the prog-rock group, [[Yes]], from the album ''Drama''.

